Class SeekCursor<KEY,​VALUE>

  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Closeable, AutoCloseable, Seeker<KEY,​VALUE>
    class SeekCursor<KEY,​VALUE>
extends Object
implements Seeker<KEY,​VALUE>
    Seeker over tree leaves, making keys/values accessible to user. Given a starting leaf and key range this cursor traverses each leaf and its right siblings as long as visited keys are within key range. Each visited key within the key range can be accessible using key(). The instances provided by Seeker.key() and Seeker.value() are mutable and overwritten with new values for every call to next() so user cannot keep references to key/value instances, expecting them to keep their values intact.

    Concurrent writes can happen in the visited nodes and tree structure may change. This implementation guards for that by re-reading if change happens underneath, but will not provide a consistent view of the data as it were when the seek starts.

    Seek can be performed forwards or backwards, returning hits in ascending or descending order respectively (as defined by Comparator.compare(Object, Object)). Direction is decided on relation between fromInclusive and toExclusive. Backwards seek is expected to be slower than forwards seek because extra care needs to be taken to make sure no keys are skipped when keys are move to the right in the tree. See detailed documentation about difficult cases below. 

     If fromInclusive <= toExclusive, then seek forwards, otherwise seek backwards

    Implementation note: there are assumptions that keys are unique in the tree.

    Note on backwards seek

    To allow for lock free concurrency control the GBPTree agree to only move keys between nodes in 'forward' direction, from left to right. This means when we do normal forward seek we never risk having keys moved 'passed' us and therefore we can always be sure that we never miss any keys when traversing the leaf nodes or end up in the middle of the range when traversing down the internal nodes. This assumption, of course, does not hold when seeking backwards. There are two complicated cases where we risk missing keys. Case 1 - Split in current node Case 2 - Split in next node while seeker is moving to that node

    Case 1 - Split in current node

    Forward seek

    Here, the seeker is seeking forward and has read K0, K1, K2 and is about to read K3. Then K4 is suddenly inserted and a split happens. Seeker will now wake up and find that he is now outside the range of (previously returned key, end of range). But he knows that he can continue to read forward until he hits the previously returned key, which is K2 and then continue to return the next key, K3. 

         Seeker->
        v
 [K0 K1 K2 K3]

     Seeker->
        v
 [K0 K1 __ __]<->[K2 K3 K4 __]
    Backward seek

    Here, the seeking is seeking backwards and has only read K3 and is about to read K2. Again, K4 is inserted, causing the same split as above. Seeker now wakes up and find that the next key he can return is K1. What he do not see is that K2 has been moved to the previous sibling and so, because he can not find the previously returned key, K3, in the current node and because the next to return, K1, is located to the far right in the current node he need to jump back to the previous sibling to find where to start again. 

          <-Seeker
           v
 [K0 K1 K2 K3]

      <-Seeker (WRONG)
           v
 [K0 K1 __ __]<->[K2 K3 K4 __]

                <-Seeker (RIGHT)
                     v
 [K0 K1 __ __]<->[K2 K3 K4 __]

    Case 2 - Split in next node while seeker is moving to that node

    Forward seek

    Seeker has read K0, K1 on node 1 and has just moved to right sibling, node 2. Now, K6 is inserted and a split happens in node 2, right sibling of node 1. Seeker wakes up and continues to read on node 2. Everything is fine. 

                       Seeker->
                      v
 1:[K0 K1 __ __]<->2:[K2 K3 K4 K5]

                   Seeker->
                      v
 1:[K0 K1 __ __]<->2:[K2 K3 __ __]<->3:[K4 K5 K6 __]
    Backward seek

    Seeker has read K4, K5 and has just moved to left sibling, node 1. Insert K6, split in node 2. Note that keys are move to node 3, passed our seeker. Seeker wakes up and see K1 as next key but misses K3 and K2. 

           <--Seeker
             v
 1:[K0 K1 K2 K3]<->2:[K4 K5 __ __]

        <-Seeker
             v
 1:[K0 K1 __ __]<->3:[K2 K3 K4 __]<->2:[K5 K6 __ __]
    To guard for this, seeker 'scout' next sibling before moving there and read first key that he expect to see, K3 in this case. By using a linked cursor to 'scout' we create a consistent read over the node gap. If there us suddenly another key when he goes there he knows that he could have missed some keys and he needs to go back until he find the place where he left off, K4.

      • traverseDownToCorrectLevel

        private void traverseDownToCorrectLevel()
                                 throws IOException
        Traverses from the root down to the node on target level (usually leaf) containing the next key that we're looking for, or the first one provided in the constructor if no result have yet been returned.

        This method is called when constructing the cursor, but also if leaf scan later on ends up on an unexpected tree node (typically due to concurrent changes, checkpoint and tree node reuse).

        Before calling this method the caller is expected to place the PageCursor at the root, by using rootCatchup. After this method returns, the PageCursor is placed on the node on target level (usually leaf) containing the next result and pos is also initialized correctly.

        Throws:
        IOException - on PageCursor error.

      • goTo

        private boolean goTo​(long pointerId,
                     long pointerGeneration,
                     String type,
                     boolean allowNoNode)
              throws IOException
        Tries to move the PageCursor to the tree node specified inside pointerId, also setting the pointer generation expectation on the next read on that new tree node.

        As with all pointers, the generation is checked for sanity and if generation looks to be in the future, there's a generation catch-up made and the read will have to be re-attempted.

        Parameters:
        pointerId - read result containing pointer id to go to.
        pointerGeneration - generation of pointerId.
        type - type of pointer, e.g. "child" or "sibling" or so.
        Returns:
        true if context was updated or PageCursor was moved, both cases meaning that caller should retry its most recent read, otherwise false meaning that nothing happened.
        Throws:
        IOException - on PageCursor error.
        TreeInconsistencyException - if allowNoNode is true and pointerId contains a "null" tree node id.

      • goToNextSibling

        private boolean goToNextSibling()
                         throws IOException
        Moves PageCursor to next sibling (read before this call into pointerId). Also, on backwards seek, calls scoutNextSibling() to be able to verify consistent read on new sibling even on concurrent writes.

        As with all pointers, the generation is checked for sanity and if generation looks to be in the future, there's a generation catch-up made and the read will have to be re-attempted.

        Returns:
        true if we should read more after this call, otherwise false to mark the end.
        Throws:
        IOException - on PageCursor error.

      • scoutNextSibling

        private boolean scoutNextSibling()
                          throws IOException
        Reads first key on next sibling, without moving the main PageCursor to that sibling. This to be able to guard for, and retry read if, concurrent writes moving keys in the "wrong" direction. The first key read here will be matched after actually moving the main PageCursor to the next sibling.

        May only be called if pointerId points to next sibling.

        Returns:
        true if first key in next sibling was read successfully, otherwise false, which means that caller should retry most recent read.
        Throws:
        IOException - on PageCursor error.

      • isResultKey

        private boolean isResultKey()
        Returns:
        whether or not the read mutableKeys is one that should be included in the result. If this method returns true then next() will return true. Returns false if this happened to be a bad read in the middle of a split or merge or so.

      • keyCountIsSane

        private boolean keyCountIsSane​(int keyCount)
        keyCount is the only value read inside a do-shouldRetry loop which is used as data fed into another read. Because of that extra assertions are made around keyCount, both inside do-shouldRetry (requesting one more round in the loop) and outside (calling this method, which may throw exception).
        Parameters:
        keyCount - key count of a tree node.
        Returns:
        true if key count is sane, i.e. positive and within max expected key count on a tree node.

        private boolean saneRead()

      • prepareToStartFromRoot

        private void prepareToStartFromRoot()
                             throws IOException
        Perform a generation catchup, updates current root and update range to start from previously returned key. Should be followed by a call to traverseDownToCorrectLevel() or if already in that method just loop again.

        Caller should retry most recent read after calling this method.

        Throws:
        IOException - on PageCursor.

      • verifyNodeGenerationInvariants

        private boolean verifyNodeGenerationInvariants()
        Verifies that the generation of the tree node arrived at matches the generation of the pointer pointing to the tree node. Generation of the node cannot be higher than the generation of the pointer - if it is then it means that the tree node has been removed (or made obsolete) and reused since we read the pointer pointing to it and that the seek is now in an invalid location and needs to be restarted from the root.
        Returns:
        true if generation matches, otherwise false if seek needs to be restarted from root.

        private boolean pointerCheckingWithGenerationCatchup​(long pointer,
                                                     boolean allowNoNode)
        Checks the provided pointer read and if not successful performs a generation catch-up with generationSupplier to allow reading that same pointer again given the updated generation context.
        Parameters:
        pointer - read result to check for success.
        allowNoNode - whether or not pointer is allowed to be "null".
        Returns:
        true if there was a generation catch-up called and generation was actually updated, this means that caller should retry its most recent read.

      • generationCatchup

        private boolean generationCatchup()
        Updates generation using the generationSupplier. If there has been a generation change since construction of this seeker or since last calling this method the generation context in this seeker is updated.
        Returns:
        true if generation was updated, which means that caller should retry its most recent read.
